Author-Name: Adrienne M. Lucas  
Author-Name: Isaac M. Mbiti  
Title: The Determinants and Consequences of School Choice Errors in Kenya 
Abstract:
 School choice systems designed to help disadvantaged groups might be
 hindered by information asymmetries. Kenyan elite secondary schools admit
 students from the entire country based on a national test score, district
 quotas, and stated school choices. We find even the highest ability
 students make school choice errors. Girls, students with lower test
 scores, and students from public and low quality schools are more likely
 to make such errors. Net of observable demographic characteristics, these
 errors are associated with a decrease in the probability that a student is
 admitted to an elite secondary school, relegating them to schools of lower
 quality.
